+## Local Setup And Web
+
+`hive setup [PROJECT_PATH] [--json]` is the supported installed-local entry point. It checks Ruby 3.4, Bundler, git, tmux, authenticated `gh`/Claude/Codex, Node/npm, QMD, the packaged Rails bundle, and SQLite before mutation. Hive may install QMD and the Rails bundle; every other missing tool or login is reported with an exact repair command. A successful run initializes or re-enrolls the real repository, repairs the daemon from the invoking stable wrapper, starts the separate web service, and verifies identified deep health.
+
+```bash
+hive setup ~/Dev/project
+hive web                         # foreground, default 127.0.0.1:4567
+hive web install                 # provision runtime + write per-user unit
+hive web start|status|restart|stop
+hive web tail
+```
+
+Automatic no-auth is allowed only for literal loopback IPs. Non-loopback binds require `--github-auth` or the explicit, loudly warned `--unsafe-no-auth`; mutations retain Rails CSRF protection in every mode. Setup reports an occupied port instead of choosing another. `hive update` refreshes an existing local web manifest/unit through the stable wrapper and otherwise directs setup; `hive uninstall` stops/removes web plus its XDG bundle/assets/cache/SQLite/log/PID state while preserving repository `.hive-state` under the normal cleanup contract.
+
 ## Bot And TUI
 
 `hive tui` opens the terminal dashboard for humans. `hive bot start|stop|status|reload|tail|install` runs the Telegram surface for human-input gates. Both read the same state as the CLI; the TUI intentionally rejects `--json`. `hive bot install [--force] [--json]` installs and enables a per-user autostart service for the bot (systemd-user on Linux, launchd on macOS) so it survives reboot/login — opt-in, mirroring `hive daemon install`; the token comes from `~/.config/hive/.env`, and `hive uninstall` removes the service.
